[3890.159349, "o", "\u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)                   General Commands Manual                   \u001b[4mBASH\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       bash - GNU Bourne-Again SHell\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mbash \u001b[22m[options] [command_string | file]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOPYRIGHT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       Bash  is  Copyright  (C)  1989-2025 by the Free Software Foundation,\u001b[m\r\n       Inc.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBash \u001b[22mis a command language interpreter that executes  commands  read\u001b[m\r\n       from the standard input, from a string, or from a file.  It is a re‐\u001b[m\r\n       implementation  and  extension  of  the Bourne shell, the historical\u001b[m\r\n       Unix command language interpreter.  \u001b[1mBash  \u001b[22malso  incorporates  useful\u001b[m\r\n       features from the \u001b[4mKorn\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mC\u001b[24m shells (\u001b[1mksh \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mcsh\u001b[22m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       POSIX is the name for a family of computing standards based on Unix.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page bash(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
